		<h2>Self Care Tips</h2>
		<main class="picturesInfo">
			<article>
				<img
					src="/diabetes-awareness-and-action/media/management/partners.jpg"
					alt="Workout partners, one doing a pushup while the other counts."
				/>
				<div class="info">
					<li>
						Self-management can also involve family members,
						friends, or other caregivers.
					</li>
					<li>
						These individuals can offer emotional support,
						participate in exercise activities, help monitor blood
						sugar, administer insulin and provide open
						communication.
					</li>
					<li>
						Enhanced social support from family and friends can help
						an individual’s belief in their ability to successfully
						manage their health needs.
					</li>
				</div>
			</article>
			<article>
				<img
					src="/diabetes-awareness-and-action/media/management/taichi.jpg"
					alt="Older woman and man practicing tai chi."
				/>
				<div class="info">
					<li>
						Managing Diabetes is not always easy. Feeling stressed,
						sad, or angry is common when you are living with
						Diabetes.
					</li>
					<li>
						Long term stress can raise your blood glucose and blood
						pressure, but you can learn ways to lower your stress.
					</li>
					<li>
						Try deep breathing, tai chi, gardening, yoga, walking,
						hiking, meditating, listening to music, and doing a
						hobby.
					</li>
				</div>
			</article>
		</main>
